For over 80 years Pinder's work was the standard reference, and was augmented only by sporadic publication of new varieties. In 1936, Hubert Herzfelder published "The Cistophori of Hadrian." His primary objective was more precise identification of mints;
               he argued that types alone were not always a reliable guide to mintage, but had to be combined with the evidence of die links, literary sources,
               and archaeology. He succeeded in identifying almost a score of mints.

Italics highlight those dies shared by two or more types. Numbering of dies begins anew at each mint or subdivision. Weights are given in grams;
               die axes show the orientation of the reverse when the obverse is at â. Where possible the direction of strike and the undertype have been
               identified in the "Overstriking" column. References to auction and sale catalogues are arranged chronologically, most recent first.

